lism: Czechoslovak Management Studies in the 1960s and 1970s -- tEcosystems Research and Policy Planning: Revisiting the Budworm Project (1972-1980) at the IIASA -- t"It is not a Question of rigidly Planning Trade" UNCTAD and the Regulation of the International Trade in the 1970s -- tPlanning the Future of World Markets: the OECD's Interfuturs Project -- tWorks Cited0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThe book opens new perspectives on the global Cold War by looking at social and economic planning. Despite the rival visions of the world that they put forward, social regulating ideas and practices were also at the core of a common project of modernity. This volume will show how social and economic knowledge circulated globally and how it was reinterpreted and appropriated in various national and local contexts.  aThe idea of planning economy and engineering social life has often been linked with Communist regimes' will of control. However, the persuasion that social and economic processes could and should be regulated was by no means limited to them. Intense debates on these issues developed already during the First World War in Europe and became globalized during the World Economic crisis. During the Cold War, such discussions fuelled competition between two models of economic and social organisation but they also revealed the convergences and complementarities between them. This ambiguity, so often overlooked in histories of the Cold War, represents the central issue of the book organized around three axes. First, it highlights how know-how on planning circulated globally and were exchanged by looking at international platforms and organizations. The volume then closely examines specificities of planning ideas and projects in the Communist and Capitalist World. Finally, it explores East-West channels generated by exchanges around issues of planning which functioned irrespective of the Iron Curtain and were exported in developing countries. The volume thus contributes to two fields undergoing a process of profound reassessment: the history of modernisation and of the Cold War.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Feb 2021) 0aCold War. 4aInternationale Organisation. 4aKalter Krieg. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh1 aZaccaria, Benedetto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMichel, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristian, Michel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aStinsky, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcKenzie, Francine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGouarné, Isabelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAndersson, Jenny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNaumann, Katja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKott, Sandrine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMatejka, Ondrej, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHutter, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristian, Michel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatějka, Ondřej, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKott, Sandrine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAutio-Sarasmo, Sari, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGodard, Simon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSom